    mechanism:
      "Direct biochemical precursor to NAD+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide), the master metabolic coenzyme that declines ~50% from age 20 to age 60. NMN is the immediate substrate for nicotinamide mononucleotide adenylyltransferases (NMNAT1, NMNAT2, NMNAT3) which convert NMN + ATP → NAD+ in the cellular salvage pathway. **Cellular uptake mechanism is contested and clinically relevant**: the 2019 Yoshino/Imai paper identified Slc12a8 as a direct NMN transporter in mouse intestinal epithelium, allowing intact NMN to enter cells without first being broken down to nicotinamide. Charles Brenner and colleagues have challenged the Slc12a8 finding methodologically, arguing NMN is dephosphorylated to nicotinamide riboside (NR) by extracellular CD73 before cellular uptake, then re-phosphorylated intracellularly. The mechanistic debate matters because if Brenner is right, NMN and NR should produce equivalent NAD+ effects (NMN is just a more expensive way to deliver NR); if Yoshino/Imai are right, NMN has a direct cellular entry route NR doesn't. The practical answer remains unclear despite considerable published research; both compounds raise NAD+ levels in human RCTs, and head-to-head comparisons have been small and short. Effects downstream of NAD+ elevation: (1) **sirtuin activation** — SIRT1 through SIRT7 are NAD+-dependent deacetylases regulating gene expression, DNA repair, mitochondrial biogenesis, circadian rhythm, glucose handling, and cellular stress responses. NAD+ depletion limits sirtuin activity; restoration enables it. (2) **PARP enzyme function** — Poly-ADP-ribose polymerases use NAD+ as substrate for DNA single-strand and double-strand break repair. Aging accumulates DNA damage; NAD+ availability bottlenecks repair capacity. (3) **CD38 substrate** — CD38 is a major NAD+-consuming enzyme that increases with age and inflammation; this is the 'NAD+ leak' aging mechanism. (4) **AMPK activation** indirectly via SIRT1; (5) **PGC-1α activation** driving mitochondrial biogenesis. Multiple human RCTs show NMN raises blood NAD+ levels in dose-dependent fashion (Yoshino 2021 100/250/500mg cohorts, Yi 2023, Pencina 2023). Effects on age-related biomarkers and physical function are emerging but not yet conclusively established at long durations.",
