    notes:
      "## Form Selection — Practical Decision\n**Standard NMN powder / capsule:** the original form; cost-effective; moderate bioavailability. The 'cellular uptake mechanism' debate (Slc12a8 vs CD73 conversion to NR) doesn't resolve cleanly here — the practical answer is that standard oral NMN raises NAD+ in human RCTs at 250mg+ doses regardless of which mechanism dominates. Most published RCT evidence is on this form.\n\n**Sublingual NMN lozenges / powder under tongue:** improved bioavailability via direct mucosal absorption bypassing first-pass hepatic metabolism. Sublingual delivery is the form Sinclair and other longevity practitioners often recommend. Real PK improvement vs swallowed capsules; cost moderately higher.\n\n**Liposomal NMN:** liposomal delivery system intended to improve cellular uptake. Quicksilver Scientific and Renue By Science are the leading liposomal product brands. Cost premium vs standard form; the bioavailability advantage over sublingual is debated. Useful for users who want every absorption-optimization layer; cost-benefit varies.\n\n**Decision frame:**\n- **Cost-conscious users:** standard NMN powder/capsule 500mg/day — most evidence; works.\n- **Bioavailability-priority users:** sublingual NMN 250mg BID — better PK, modest cost premium.\n- **Aggressive longevity-stack users:** liposomal NMN as part of comprehensive protocol — every layer optimized.\n- **NMN vs NR decision:** see the Sinclair-Brenner framing in the NR entry — the practical answer is that both work; running both isn't redundant per current evidence; NR has more long-term safety data; NMN may have direct-uptake advantage if Slc12a8 mechanism is correct.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n250mg/day × 2 weeks to assess tolerance, then 500mg/day AM, fasted, ongoing. Track subjectively over 8–12 weeks (energy, clarity, recovery, sleep). The longevity benefit is largely cellular-maintenance over years, not acute response — set expectations accordingly. Bracket with NAD+ blood level testing if available (specialty labs offer this; not necessary for protocol but informative for engaged users).\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nLayer with: NR 300mg/day (if running both NAD precursors — most longevity practitioners run one or both, not strictly redundant), TMG 1–2g/day (methylation cofactor — see TMG entry), Resveratrol 250–500mg/day (sirtuin activator downstream of NAD+), Pterostilbene 100mg/day (resveratrol analog with better native bioavailability), Spermidine 1mg/day (autophagy via complementary mechanism), Urolithin A 500mg/day (mitophagy via complementary mechanism), Trigonelline 100mg/day (additional NAD precursor at lower cost), Rapamycin 5–10mg weekly pulse (mTOR-pathway longevity activator). The full longevity stack is built around NAD+ pathway support + downstream sirtuin/autophagy/mitophagy activation + dietary/lifestyle foundations (caloric restriction or time-restricted eating, structured exercise, sleep optimization, dietary protein adequacy).\n\n## NMN vs NR — Decision Frame (Honest Assessment)\nBoth raise NAD+ in human RCTs. Both are well-tolerated short-term. The Sinclair-Brenner mechanistic debate hasn't resolved cleanly. The practical differences:\n\n**NMN:** more recent commercial entrant; higher cost; FDA regulatory status contested (2022 controversy); the Slc12a8 direct-uptake mechanism, if real, would distinguish it from NR; less long-term safety data than NR.\n\n**NR (Niagen):** longer commercial track record (Niagen since 2013); FDA GRAS status confirmed; more long-term safety data; more human RCT evidence on broader endpoints; mid-range cost; the Brenner-laboratory-developed compound with substantial published research.\n\n**Practical recommendation:** users wanting the most-evidence-backed, regulatorily-clearest NAD precursor → NR. Users running comprehensive longevity stacks may include both. Cost-conscious users → start with NR (more evidence-to-cost; clearer regulatory status); add NMN if curious about the Slc12a8 mechanism or wanting to layer.\n\n## Methyl-Depletion Concern + TMG Pairing\nNMN/NR elevate NAD+, which is partly catabolized via N-methylation (NNMT enzyme) consuming S-adenosylmethionine (SAMe). Chronic high-dose NAD+ precursor users theoretically deplete methyl groups, which could affect homocysteine metabolism, neurotransmitter synthesis, DNA methylation. The concern is more theoretical than clinically established — but the TMG (trimethylglycine / betaine) pairing is widespread in longevity protocols as a methyl-donor insurance policy. Standard TMG dose 1–2g/day with NMN/NR. See TMG entry for full discussion.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, sublingual lozenge, or liposomal liquid. Fasted AM dosing typical. Sublingual: hold under tongue 60–90 seconds before swallowing for mucosal absorption. Liposomal: as directed by product (some liquid, some encapsulated).\n\n## Synergies\n**NR:** related NAD precursor; combinations common in longevity stacks. **TMG:** methyl-donor pairing for chronic NMN/NR use. **Resveratrol:** sirtuin activation downstream of NAD+ elevation. **Trigonelline:** alternative NAD precursor at lower cost. **Urolithin A:** mitophagy via complementary mechanism. **Spermidine:** autophagy via complementary mechanism. **Exercise:** the most evidence-supported NAD+ maintenance intervention; supplementation works alongside, not instead of, structured exercise.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nYoshino 2021 (n=80 prediabetic postmenopausal women, 250mg/day × 10 weeks): improved insulin sensitivity, walking endurance. Yi 2023 (n=80 healthy adults, 300/600/900mg/day × 60 days): dose-dependent NAD+ elevation, walking endurance improvement. Pencina 2023 (n=30 healthy older adults, 1000mg/day × 28 days): NAD+ elevation, no adverse signals. Igarashi 2022 (n=42 healthy older men, 250mg/day × 12 weeks): muscle strength improvements. Liao 2021 (n=48 amateur runners, 600/1200mg/day × 6 weeks): aerobic capacity improvements.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanistically grounded; multiple human RCTs showing NAD+ elevation; effect on age-related functional outcomes accumulating but not yet conclusively established at long durations. Long-term safety data limited to ~60 days in formal RCTs; longer real-world use is common without documented harm.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid mechanistic case for NAD+ pool restoration; multiple RCTs showing dose-dependent NAD+ elevation and modest functional improvements (insulin sensitivity, walking endurance, muscle strength); the long-term aging-biomarker evidence is emerging but not yet conclusive. Anecdote: extensive longevity-community use; subjective reports vary (some users report distinct energy/clarity improvements within 2–4 weeks; others note minimal subjective response despite measurable NAD+ elevation). Decision frame: foundational NAD precursor for longevity stacks; the cellular-maintenance benefit accrues over years rather than producing acute response; cost/benefit favors inclusion for users running comprehensive longevity protocols; cost-conscious users may prefer NR (more evidence-to-cost) or trigonelline (lowest-cost NAD precursor).",
