    mechanism:
      "Naturally occurring amino acid derivative consisting of glycine with three methyl groups attached to the nitrogen (hence 'tri-methyl-glycine'). Found in beets, spinach, quinoa, wheat bran, and other foods; the name 'betaine' originated from beets (Beta vulgaris) where it was first isolated. **Mechanism — methyl donor function**: TMG donates one of its three methyl groups via betaine-homocysteine methyltransferase (BHMT), converting homocysteine + TMG → methionine + dimethylglycine (DMG). This pathway is one of two primary methods for homocysteine recycling in the body (the other being the folate-dependent MTR pathway requiring B12 and folate). The methionine produced is then activated to S-adenosylmethionine (SAMe) — the universal methyl donor used in 200+ methyltransferase reactions throughout cellular biochemistry including: DNA methylation, neurotransmitter synthesis, phospholipid methylation, NAD+ catabolism via NNMT, creatine synthesis, carnitine synthesis. **Why TMG matters in NAD+ longevity protocols**: NAD+ elevation from NMN/NR supplementation drives increased NAD+ catabolism via the NNMT (nicotinamide N-methyltransferase) enzyme, which methylates excess nicotinamide to 1-methylnicotinamide (1-MNA) for excretion. NNMT consumes one methyl group per nicotinamide molecule processed. Chronic high-dose NMN/NR users theoretically deplete methyl groups (SAMe → SAH conversion exceeds methyl regeneration capacity), affecting downstream methylation-dependent processes. TMG pairing with NMN/NR provides methyl-donor backup ensuring SAMe pool maintenance. The methyl-depletion concern is more theoretical than clinically established — but the TMG pairing is widespread in longevity protocols as practical insurance. **Mechanism — homocysteine reduction**: independent of NAD+ context, TMG reduces elevated homocysteine in users with elevated baseline (normal range <12 μmol/L; cardiovascular risk elevation typically >15 μmol/L). RCTs show 5–8 μmol/L reductions at 3–6g/day TMG. The homocysteine reduction is via the BHMT pathway — bypassing folate / B12 dependency and providing an alternative homocysteine-clearing mechanism. **Mechanism — osmolyte function**: TMG is an osmolyte protecting cells against osmotic and hydrostatic stress. Cellular osmoregulation matters in renal medullary cells (high salt) and cardiomyocytes (mechanical stress). The osmolyte function is a smaller part of TMG's clinical relevance but explains some niche use cases. **Performance use**: TMG (typically called 'betaine' in the performance space) at 2.5g/day has shown modest strength and power output improvements in resistance-training cohorts — Cholewa 2013 et al. The mechanism is debated; possibilities include creatine synthesis support, methyl-donor effects on training-related gene expression, or osmolyte effects on cellular hydration during high-intensity work.",
