    sourcingNotes:
      "OTC supplement; widely available. Bulk powder is the most cost-effective form (BulkSupplements, NOW Foods Betaine Anhydrous). Capsule forms also widely available. Reputable brands: Thorne Methyl-Guard Plus (TMG + methylfolate + methyl-B12 + B6 — comprehensive methylation support), Designs for Health Betaine HCl (note: this product combines betaine with HCl for digestive support — different use case from pure TMG methyl-donor function), Jarrow Formulas TMG. Cost: ~$15–25/month at 2g/day from bulk powder.",
    notes:
      "## Why TMG Pairs with NMN/NR — The Methyl-Depletion Mechanism\nNAD+ supplementation increases NAD+ catabolism. The dominant catabolic pathway runs through NNMT (nicotinamide N-methyltransferase), which methylates excess nicotinamide (NAD+ breakdown product) to 1-methylnicotinamide for renal excretion. NNMT consumes one methyl group per nicotinamide molecule processed. Each methyl group consumption converts SAMe → SAH (S-adenosylhomocysteine). SAH then breaks down to homocysteine, which must be remethylated back to methionine to regenerate SAMe.\n\nHomocysteine remethylation has two pathways: (1) the folate / B12-dependent MTR pathway (methionine synthase), and (2) the betaine-dependent BHMT pathway (betaine-homocysteine methyltransferase). TMG supplementation feeds the BHMT pathway directly. For users running NMN/NR chronically, the methylation demand increases proportional to NAD+ catabolic flux. Whether this produces clinically meaningful methyl depletion in well-fed users with adequate folate/B12 is debated — but the TMG pairing is cheap, well-tolerated, and provides practical insurance.\n\n## TMG Dose by Use Case\n**NMN/NR pairing (longevity stack):** 1–2g/day with the NAD precursor. Most users settle here.\n\n**Homocysteine reduction:** 3–6g/day for users with elevated homocysteine (>12 μmol/L). RCT-level evidence at this dose range (Olthof 2003: 6g/day × 6 weeks reduced homocysteine ~12% in healthy adults; larger reductions in elevated-baseline cohorts).\n\n**Performance use:** 2.5g/day — the dose used in performance-supplement studies (Cholewa 2013, Trepanowski 2011).\n\n**Therapeutic homocystinuria** (genetic homocysteine elevation): up to 9g/day under physician supervision. FDA-approved via Cystadane (anhydrous betaine) for homocystinuria.\n\n## TMAO Concern — Honest Framing\nThe trimethylamine N-oxide (TMAO) cardiovascular concern is real but often overstated for typical TMG supplementation. The pathway: TMG → trimethylamine (TMA) by gut bacteria → TMAO by hepatic FMO3. Elevated TMAO correlates with cardiovascular disease risk in epidemiological data. Causality vs correlation is debated; some research suggests TMAO is a marker rather than driver.\n\nFor practical decisions: chronic high-dose TMG (>3g/day) elevates TMAO meaningfully; standard NAD-pairing doses (1–2g/day) produce modest effects. Users with established cardiovascular disease or elevated baseline TMAO may want to be cautious. Users running TMG primarily for homocysteine reduction with elevated baseline homocysteine likely benefit from the homocysteine reduction more than they're harmed by modest TMAO elevation — but this is an individual risk-benefit calculation worth discussing with a prescriber.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n1g/day with NMN or NR (typically AM dosing). Track no specific subjective markers — TMG's effect is largely silent (methyl-donor support, not subjectively perceptible). For homocysteine-targeting users: 3g/day BID with food, bracket with homocysteine labs at baseline and 8–12 weeks.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\nFor comprehensive methylation support: TMG 2g/day + methylfolate (5-MTHF) 400mcg + methylcobalamin (methyl-B12) 1000mcg + pyridoxal-5-phosphate (P5P / active B6) 25mg. This 'methylation triumvirate plus' addresses both the BHMT and MTR pathways for homocysteine clearance plus B6 for the transsulfuration pathway. The Thorne Methyl-Guard Plus formulation captures this approach in a single product.\n\nFor MTHFR polymorphism users (677TT or 1298CC homozygotes with reduced folate-dependent homocysteine clearance): TMG dosing may be more important than for general population because the folate pathway is compromised. 2–3g/day TMG + methylfolate 400mcg–1mg.\n\nFor performance users: 2.5g/day in resistance-training context.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, powder, or tablet. With food preferred to reduce rare GI sensitivity. Powder mixes into water or any beverage (slightly sweet taste — actually pleasant relative to most supplement powders).\n\n## Synergies\n**NMN / NR:** the central pairing rationale — methyl-donor support for chronic NAD+ precursor use. **Methylfolate (5-MTHF):** comprehensive methylation pathway support. **Methyl-B12 (methylcobalamin):** comprehensive methylation pathway support. **B6 (P5P):** transsulfuration pathway for homocysteine clearance. **Creatine:** methyl-donor flow into creatine synthesis (TMG donates methyl group → DMG → glycine + creatine pathway).\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nOlthof 2003 (n=12 healthy adults, 6g/day × 6 weeks): 12% homocysteine reduction. Steenge 2003 (n=12 obese, 6g/day × 6 weeks): 12% homocysteine reduction. Cholewa 2013 (n=34 resistance-trained men, 2.5g/day × 6 weeks): improved bench press training volume, vertical jump. Trepanowski 2011 (n=23 cyclists, 2.5g/day × 14 days): improved sprint performance. Wallis 2005 (n=10 cyclists, 2.5g/day × 7 days): improved time-to-exhaustion. Schwab 2002 (n=27, 4g/day × 12 weeks in obese subjects): no change in insulin sensitivity — TMG is not a metabolic compound in the metformin/berberine sense; the methylation and homocysteine effects are the primary clinical contributions.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-established (FDA-approved Cystadane for homocystinuria). Homocysteine-lowering RCT evidence solid. Performance-use evidence emerging but consistent. NAD-pairing rationale is mechanistically grounded; clinical RCT evidence specifically for the NMN+TMG or NR+TMG combination is limited (most users pair them empirically based on the methylation logic).\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: well-established for homocysteine reduction; modest evidence for performance use; mechanistic rationale for NAD+ pairing. Anecdote: widespread inclusion in longevity stacks alongside NMN/NR; subjective effects largely silent (methyl-donor support is mechanism-driven, not subjectively perceptible). Decision frame: foundational pairing for chronic NMN/NR users; standalone use for homocysteine reduction in elevated-baseline users; useful performance adjunct in resistance-training contexts; cost/benefit favors inclusion at standard doses for users already running NAD precursors.",
