    mechanism:
      "Polyphenolic stilbene compound found in red wine, grape skins, Japanese knotweed (Polygonum cuspidatum — the primary commercial source for supplement-grade resveratrol due to higher concentration than grape sources), peanuts, and various berries. The compound exists in two isomers: trans-resveratrol (the bioactive, clinically-relevant form) and cis-resveratrol (less bioactive). Commercial products should specify trans-resveratrol content. **Mechanism — sirtuin activation**: resveratrol allosterically activates SIRT1 (and to lesser extent SIRT3, SIRT6), the NAD+-dependent deacetylase that mediates many of the cellular benefits of caloric restriction and NAD+ elevation. SIRT1 activation drives downstream effects including PGC-1α activation (mitochondrial biogenesis), FOXO transcription factor activation (stress resistance), eNOS activation (vascular function), p53 modulation (DNA damage response). The 2003 Sinclair laboratory paper at Harvard demonstrated resveratrol's SIRT1 activation in yeast and extended yeast lifespan — the foundational paper that drove resveratrol's longevity-supplement reputation. **Mechanism — beyond sirtuins**: resveratrol has substantial AMPK activation independent of SIRT1, mTOR pathway modulation, NF-κB inhibition (anti-inflammatory), Nrf2 activation (antioxidant response element pathway), estrogen receptor partial agonism (relevant for hormone-sensitive populations), and direct antioxidant effects. The mechanism is genuinely multi-pathway. **Mechanism — bioavailability is the dominant practical issue**: standard oral trans-resveratrol has poor bioavailability — peak plasma concentrations are <1% of administered dose due to extensive intestinal and hepatic glucuronidation/sulfation. The compound is heavily metabolized to glucuronide and sulfate conjugates within minutes of absorption. Whether these conjugates retain biological activity is debated — some research suggests tissue-specific deconjugation regenerates active resveratrol locally; other research suggests the conjugates are largely inactive. The bioavailability limitation has driven development of multiple alternative forms (liposomal, phytosome, micronized) and the related compound pterostilbene (methylated analog with substantially better native bioavailability). **The Sinclair-vs-skeptics debate**: David Sinclair has been the most prominent advocate for resveratrol's longevity benefits; the GlaxoSmithKline acquisition of Sirtris Pharmaceuticals (Sinclair's company) for $720 million in 2008 was based on resveratrol-and-derivatives sirtuin activator development. Subsequent failure of Sirtris's lead resveratrol-derivative drug SRT2104 in clinical trials, combined with reproducibility concerns about some of the foundational sirtuin-activation mechanism research, has produced a more skeptical mainstream pharmacological position. Honest framing: resveratrol has real biological effects in vitro and in animal models; human translation has been mixed; the bioavailability issue likely explains some of the human translation failure; the compound remains a reasonable component of comprehensive longevity stacks but is not the standalone-magic-bullet the early Sinclair-era marketing suggested.",
