    mechanism:
      "Polyamine compound (along with putrescine and spermine) involved in cellular growth, DNA stabilization, and translational regulation. Synthesized endogenously from putrescine via spermidine synthase; declines significantly with age (~50% reduction from age 20 to age 70 in most tissues). Found in foods at variable concentrations: highest in wheat germ (~244 mg/kg), aged cheese (especially Cheddar, Parmesan ~60–200 mg/kg), natto (~250 mg/kg), soybeans, mushrooms, mature legumes. **Mechanism — autophagy induction**: spermidine is the most validated autophagy-inducing compound in supplement landscape. The mechanism involves multiple pathways: (1) **inhibition of EP300 acetyltransferase** — a key cellular switch; EP300 normally acetylates and inactivates autophagy proteins (ATG5, ATG7, LC3); spermidine inhibits EP300, allowing autophagy machinery activation. This is the central mechanism per Madeo and colleagues' 2018 Science Advances paper. (2) **AMPK pathway activation** indirectly. (3) **mTOR pathway modulation** — though the primary mechanism is EP300 inhibition rather than mTOR direct effects. (4) **Hypusination of eIF5A** — spermidine is the substrate for eIF5A hypusination, a unique post-translational modification that activates translation of autophagy and mitochondrial proteins; this is potentially the most distinctive spermidine mechanism. **Why autophagy matters for longevity**: autophagy is the cellular 'recycling' process — degradation and removal of damaged proteins, organelles, and aggregates. Autophagy declines with age, contributing to accumulation of cellular damage. Caloric restriction and time-restricted eating activate autophagy as a major mechanism of their longevity benefits; spermidine activates autophagy pharmacologically without dietary restriction. Rapamycin also activates autophagy (via mTOR inhibition); spermidine activates via different mechanism (EP300 inhibition); combinations are mechanistically rational. **Mechanism — beyond autophagy**: anti-inflammatory effects, mitochondrial function support, cardioprotective effects (reduced cardiac hypertrophy in animal models), neuroprotective effects, immune function support (enhanced T-cell function in aged mice). **Human longevity evidence**: Eisenberg 2016 (Nature Medicine) is the foundational human paper — analysis of >800 elderly Italians from the Bruneck cohort showed dietary spermidine intake inversely correlated with all-cause mortality, with the highest tertile of intake associated with 5-year longer survival. The study is observational, not RCT, but the effect size is substantial and the mechanism is plausible. Subsequent human trials have shown spermidine supplementation improves cognitive function in older adults at risk of dementia (Schwarz 2018) and improves cardiac function markers. The longevity-supplement community's interest in spermidine accelerated significantly post-Eisenberg 2016.",
